quizzes.textContent:
[h1]The for Loop[/h1]

The [b]for [/b]loop is used when you know in advance how many times the script should run. [code format="php"][b]for [/b](init; test; increment) {
   code to be executed;
}[/code]
[b]Parameters:[/b]
[b]init[/b]: Initialize the loop counter value
[b]test[/b]: Evaluates each time the loop is iterated, continuing if evaluates to [b]true[/b], and ending if it evaluates to [b]false[/b]
[b]increment:[/b] Increases the loop counter value
[note]Each of the parameter expressions can be empty or contain multiple expressions that are separated with [b]commas[/b]. 
In the [b]for[/b] statement, the parameters are separated with [b]semicolons[/b].[/note]

quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to print the variable "name" 10 times.
[!raw!]
$name = "Bruce";
for({0}; {1}; {2})   {
   echo $name; 
}

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]The for Loop[/h1]

The example below displays the numbers from 0 to 5:[code format="php" codeId="480"][b]for [/b]($a = 0; $a < 6; $a++) {
   echo "Value of a : ". $a . "<br />";
}[/code]
[b]Result: [/b][img id="2322" width="100%"]
[note]The [b]for[/b] loop in the example above first sets the variable [b]$a[/b] to 0, then checks for the condition ($a < 6). If the condition is true, it runs the code. After that, it increments $a ($a++).[/note]
